const char* const Kernel_ComputePowerProduct_2_operator = "returns the power product of pw and qw . Let $ {p}^{(w)} = (p,w_p), p\\in\\mathbb{R}^2, w_p\\in\\mathbb{R}$ and $ {q}^{(w)}=(q,w_q), q\\in\\mathbb{R}^2, w_q\\in\\mathbb{R}$ be two weighted points. The power product , also called power distance between $ {p}^{(w)}$ and $ {q}^{(w)}$ is defined as \\[ \\Pi({p}^{(w)},{q}^{(w)}) = {\\|{p-q}\\|^2-w_p-w_q} \\] where $ \\|{p-q}\\|$ is the Euclidean distance between $ p$ and $ q$ . The weighted points $ {p}^{(w)}$ and $ {q}^{(w)}$ are said to be orthogonal iff $ \\Pi{({p}^{(w)},{q}^{(w)})}\n= 0$ . Three weighted points have, in 2D, a unique common orthogonal weighted point called the power circle . The power segment will denote the weighted point orthogonal to two weighted points on the line defined by these two points. Returns: Kernel::FT";
const char* const Kernel_ComputePowerProduct_3_operator = "returns the power product of pw and qw . Let $ {p}^{(w)}=(p,w_p), p\\in\\mathbb{R}^3, w_p\\in\\mathbb{R}$ and $ {q}^{(w)}=(q,w_q), q\\in\\mathbb{R}^3, w_q\\in\\mathbb{R}$ be two weighted points. The power product , also called power distance between $ {p}^{(w)}$ and $ {q}^{(w)}$ is defined as \\[ \\Pi({p}^{(w)},{q}^{(w)}) = {\\|{p-q}\\|^2-w_p-w_q} \\] where $ \\|{p-q}\\|$ is the Euclidean distance between $ p$ and $ q$ . The weighted points $ {p}^{(w)}$ and $ {q}^{(w)}$ are said to be orthogonal iff $ \\Pi{({p}^{(w)},{q}^{(w)})}\n= 0$ . Four weighted points have, in 3D, a unique common orthogonal weighted point called the power sphere . The weighted point orthogonal to three weighted points in the plane defined by these three points is called the power circle . The power segment will denote the weighted point orthogonal to two weighted points on the line defined by these two points. Returns: Kernel::FT";
